Qu. 1

There is an obvious relationship between the loan grade and the amount interest paid, suggesting that grade A has the least risk and grade G the most risk.

loans_data %>% 
  ggplot() +
  aes(x = loan_amnt, y = int_rate, colour = grade) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.5) +
  facet_wrap(~ grade) +
  labs(
    x = "Loan Amount ($)",
    y = "Interest Rate (%)",
    title = "Interest Rate vs. Loan Amount",
    subtitle = "By loan grade",
    colour = "Loan Grade"
  ) +
  theme_bw()

Qu. 2

library(viridis)

mean_loan_amnt <- loans_data %>%
  group_by(grade, int_rate) %>% 
  summarise(
    mean_loan_amnt = mean(loan_amnt),
    mean_int_rate = mean(int_rate),
    .groups = "drop"
  )
  
mean_loan_amnt %>%   
  ggplot() +
  aes(x = grade, y = mean_loan_amnt, fill = mean_int_rate) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  labs(
    x = "\nLoan Grade",
    y = "\nMean Loan Amount ($)\n",
    title = "Mean Loan Amount vs. Loan Grade",
    subtitle = "By mean interest rate",
    fill = "Mean\nInterest Rate"
  ) +
  theme_bw() +
  scale_fill_continuous(type = "viridis") +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = function(x) format(x, scientific = FALSE))

Qu. 3

loans_data %>% 
  ggplot() +
  aes(x = loan_amnt, y = int_rate) +
  geom_point(colour = "brown", alpha = 0.5) +
  facet_grid(grade ~ purpose) +
  labs(
    x = "\nLoan Amount ($)",
    y = "Interest Rate (%)",
    title = "Interest Rate vs. Loan Amount",
    subtitle = "By loan grade and purpose"
  ) +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, vjust = 0.5, hjust=1))

loans_data %>% 
  ggplot() +
  aes(x = loan_amnt, y = int_rate, colour = grade) +
  geom_line(alpha = 0.5) +
  facet_wrap(~ purpose) +
  labs(
    x = "\nLoan Amount ($)",
    y = "Interest Rate (%)\n",
    title = "Interest Rate vs. Loan Amount",
    subtitle = "By loan grade and purpose",
    colour = "Loan Grade"
  ) +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, vjust = 0.5, hjust=1))
